INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0f1cf5a3-67ef-4ef4-9a12-48f5ab6cc6fa',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$RabbitMQ Idempotency — Designing Consumers to Safely Handle Duplicate Messages$escape$,
  $escape$RabbitMQ can redeliver messages when a consumer crashes before sending `basic.ack`, or when a channel is closed mid-processing. This means your consumer logic must be idempotent — running it twice must produce the same outcome as running it once.

The safest pattern is a deduplication store keyed on the message's `messageId` property (set by the publisher via `IBasicProperties.MessageId`). Before processing, check a Redis SET or a DB unique constraint for that ID. If it exists, `basic.ack` immediately and return. If not, process and persist the ID atomically — ideally in the same DB transaction as your business write.

Avoid relying on RabbitMQ's built-in `redelivered` flag (`ea.Redelivered`). It's `true` only when the *same channel* redelivers; after a broker restart or queue failover the flag resets to `false`, giving you a false sense of safety.

For at-least-once delivery with quorum queues, also set `x-delivery-limit` to cap runaway redeliveries and pair it with a dead-letter exchange so poison messages don't loop forever.$escape$,
  $escape$channel.BasicConsume(queue: "orders", autoAck: false, consumer: consumer);

consumer.Received += async (_, ea) =>
{
    var msgId = ea.BasicProperties.MessageId;

    if (await dedupeStore.ExistsAsync(msgId))
    {
        channel.BasicAck(ea.DeliveryTag, multiple: false);
        return;
    }

    await using var tx = await db.BeginTransactionAsync();
    await ProcessOrderAsync(ea.Body.ToArray(), tx);
    await dedupeStore.SetAsync(msgId, ttl: TimeSpan.FromHours(24));
    await tx.CommitAsync();

    channel.BasicAck(ea.DeliveryTag, multiple: false);
};$escape$,
  $escape$csharp$escape$,
