INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9aa42163-dcb6-487f-9741-3f838ca48f63',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$RabbitMQ Developer's Guide to Redis Queues — Pub/Sub vs Streams vs Lists$escape$,
  $escape$Redis offers three queue-like primitives, each mapping differently to RabbitMQ concepts. Lists (LPUSH/BRPOP) mimic a basic queue but lack RabbitMQ's acknowledgement model — a crashed consumer loses the message entirely. Pub/Sub (PUBLISH/SUBSCRIBE) is fire-and-forget, equivalent to a fanout exchange with no durable queue binding; messages vanish if no subscriber is listening at publish time. Neither persists reliably by default.

Streams (XADD/XREADGROUP) are the closest analog to RabbitMQ's durable queues with consumer groups. You get explicit ACKs (XACK), per-consumer group offsets analogous to independent queue consumers, and a pending entry list (PEL) as a dead-letter equivalent for unacked messages. With appendonly yes in redis.conf, Streams survive restarts — unlike Lists, which lose in-flight messages even with RDB snapshots enabled.

For RabbitMQ migrations: if your consumers rely on basic.ack / basic.nack with requeue semantics, Redis Streams is the only viable path. Pub/Sub works for fanout exchange patterns where durability isn't required. Never use Lists for at-least-once delivery — there's no equivalent to RabbitMQ's unacked message redelivery on disconnect.$escape$,
  $escape$import redis

r = redis.Redis()

# Producer: equivalent to basic.publish to a durable queue
r.xadd("tasks", {"job": "resize_image", "id": "42"})

# Consumer group: equivalent to RabbitMQ consumer with manual ack
r.xgroup_create("tasks", "workers", id="0", mkstream=True)

messages = r.xreadgroup("workers", "consumer-1", {"tasks": ">"}, count=1, block=5000)
for stream, entries in messages:
    for msg_id, data in entries:
        print(f"Processing {data}")
        r.xack("tasks", "workers", msg_id)  # explicit ACK — like basic.ack in AMQP$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
