INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '8ef5dd2f-b458-481b-aa5f-fc209a5ab503',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$RabbitMQ Consumer Testing — Isolating Handlers Without a Running Broker$escape$,
  $escape$Testing RabbitMQ consumers doesn't require a live broker. The key is separating your message handler logic from the AMQP transport layer. In the .NET RabbitMQ.Client, your consumer typically inherits from `AsyncEventingBasicConsumer` or implements `IBasicConsumer`. Extract the handler body into a pure function or service that accepts `BasicDeliverEventArgs` — then unit-test that function directly, constructing `IBasicProperties` and the raw byte payload yourself.

For integration tests, use `EasyNetQ`'s `IBus` abstraction or inject a fake `IModel` via `NSubstitute`/`Moq`. Intercept `BasicAck`, `BasicNack`, and `BasicReject` calls to assert exactly what your consumer does on success, deserialization failure, or a domain exception. This validates your dead-letter and retry logic — the parts most likely to silently break.

For full-stack tests, `Testcontainers.RabbitMQ` spins up a real broker in Docker. Publish to the actual exchange, consume via your registered queue binding, and assert side effects. Use `management` plugin endpoints (`/api/queues/{vhost}/{name}`) to inspect queue depth and message counts without coupling to your application code.$escape$,
  $escape$// Unit-test the handler in isolation — no broker needed
var handler = new OrderMessageHandler(mockOrderService);

var props = new Mock<IBasicProperties>();
props.Setup(p => p.MessageId).Returns("msg-001");
props.Setup(p => p.ContentType).Returns("application/json");

var body = JsonSerializer.SerializeToUtf8Bytes(new OrderCreated { OrderId = 42 });
var args = new BasicDeliverEventArgs
{
    DeliveryTag = 1,
    BasicProperties = props.Object,
    Body = new ReadOnlyMemory<byte>(body)
};

await handler.HandleAsync(args, CancellationToken.None);

mockOrderService.Verify(s => s.ProcessAsync(It.Is<OrderCreated>(o => o.OrderId == 42)), Times.Once);$escape$,
  $escape$csharp$escape$,
